snippet.textDisplay: I'm sorry, but saying that the killing of three bankers just out of nowhere is linked to rich vs. poor is heavily related to the super rats, the garbage and the cut in state spending. All those things are supposed to show, that there already is a social divide (the rats are large because the infrastructure is not running anymore, the garbage is on the streets because the trash collectors are most likely striking etc.). Just looking at the news today, it's not hard to see why a masked guy killing three young bankers could immediately be seen as a political statement and thus a fuse for already existing social tensions to errupt. I feel like a lot about this part was intentionally misunderstood to give it a sin here.

snippet.textDisplay: WARNING** SPOILER+RANT...The biggest issue I have with this movie is the circumstances of how Bruce's parents are killed. This movie changes a fundamental aspect of  what helped Bruce become the Batman. The movie shows them leaving the theater because of the riots, which leads to their murder. That entirely ruins the creation of Batman in my opinion. Bruce is suppose to feel guilty for being scared in the theater and wanting to leave early. Because Bruce was scared and they left early, his parents were killed that night. The guilt of being part of what killed his parents helped him become the Batman. Yet the movie blames the Joker for the riots, which leads to them leaving the theater early, and then to their deaths. As Bruce is  "The World's Greatest Detective" he would be able to make this connection in his later years, and blaming Joker for his parent's death instead of himself. To me this would change Batman as he would no longer blame himself, but instead the Joker. Without the guilt and with only anger towards the one who caused his parents death, how would that Batman look?

snippet.textDisplay:
Many things wrong with this video

First up, the sign.
Stores hire sign people, that’s a thing, nothing wrong with that.He ran after the thieves because he feared being reprimanded for losing it. yes, he did tell his boss that he got robbed, but of course, his boss didn’t care.

Next up, the gun.
Revolvers can hold more than just 5-6 rounds in the cylinder. It’s perfectly commonplace and normal for revolvers to be able to contain 8 rounds

Next up, the bathroom scene
That scene portrayed the beginning of Arthur’s transition into becoming the joker. Very integral moment.

Next up, the totally inconceivable idea that a joker movie contains batman references. kinda self explanatory.

And finally the 11:11 bits, you mentioned “lack of consistency” when referring to the Murray clock, when in the beginning you explained that 11 symbolized shyness, anxiety, etc. in the Murray scene arthur is none of these things, he’s calm, cool, and collected. It symbolizes that arthur is no longer anxious and shy, he embraced his insanity and his illness.
Cinema Sins is dead, and the people who made it great, are now responsible for killing it.
snippet.textOriginal:
Many things wrong with this video

First up, the sign.
Stores hire sign people, that’s a thing, nothing wrong with that.He ran after the thieves because he feared being reprimanded for losing it. yes, he *did* tell his boss that he got robbed, but of course, his boss didn’t care.

Next up, the gun. 
Revolvers can hold more than just 5-6 *rounds* in the cylinder. It’s perfectly commonplace and normal for revolvers to be able to contain 8 *rounds*

Next up, the bathroom scene
That scene portrayed the beginning of Arthur’s transition into becoming the joker. Very integral moment.

Next up, the *totally inconceivable* idea that a *joker movie* contains *batman references.* kinda self explanatory.

And finally the 11:11 bits, you mentioned “lack of consistency” when referring to the Murray clock, when in the beginning you explained that 11 symbolized shyness, anxiety, etc. in the Murray scene arthur is none of these things, he’s calm, cool, and collected. It symbolizes that arthur is no longer anxious and shy, he embraced his insanity and his illness.
Cinema Sins is dead, and the people who made it great, are now responsible for killing it.

snippet.textDisplay: at 6:09, its standard for .38 revolvers to hold 8 shots. I'm not entirely sure if the one in the movie is a .38 but considering its a mini snubnose its most likely not a higher caliber. The reason higher caliber revolvers only hold 6 is because if they held more it would compromise the structure of the cylinder. .38s are small enough to hold 8 in a cylinder without compromising the structure of the cylinder.
